This repository contains a complete end-to-end analysis pipeline for two-color SMLM / TIRF microscopy data (e.g., TIRF 560 and TIRF 647). 
The pipeline is designed to extract dipole distances, orientations, and trajectories while robustly handling crowded regions, ambiguous pairings, and physically undefined cases.
The code prioritizes scientific correctness, reproducibility, and transparent visualization rather than aggressive filtering.

Overview
The pipeline performs the following steps:

01) Loads and filters localization data for two fluorescence channels
02) Removes ambiguous puncta in crowded regions (same-channel and opposite-channel proximity)
03) Enforces one-to-one dipole pairing per frame
04) Computes dipole geometry (distance, azimuth angle Φ, polar angle θ)
05) Tracks dipoles across frames using midpoint-based assignment
06) Visualizes dipole distributions and orientations using multiple complementary plots
All original diagnostic and visualization plots are preserved to support exploratory analysis.

Input Requirements
The pipeline expects two CSV files with the following columns:
A. id
B. frame
C. x [nm]
D. y [nm]
E. uncertainty_xy [nm]
F. intensity [photon]

Example input files:
TIRF560_imageregperformed.csv
TIRF647_imageregperformed.csv

Key Features and Safeguards

Threshold-Based Filtering
Localizations are filtered by localization uncertainty, photon count, and spatial region of interest. All thresholds are user-adjustable at the top of the script.

Same-Channel Crowding and Ambiguity Removal
If two puncta in the same channel are closer than the pairing radius and either has an opposite-channel neighbor within that radius, all involved puncta are removed. This conservative rule prevents over-counting in dense regions, false dipole assignments, and track contamination across frames.

One-to-One Dipole Pairing (Per Frame)
Within each frame, dipole pairing is restricted to a single C1–C2 match per puncta. Pairing is solved using a Hungarian assignment algorithm, and only pairs within the specified distance threshold are retained. This eliminates many-to-many dipole artifacts common in dense SMLM data.

Dipole Geometry Computation
For each valid dipole pair, the end-to-end distance is computed. The azimuth angle Φ (in degrees) is calculated using atan2. The polar angle θ (in degrees) is computed using a physical rod-length model.

Importantly, θ is not silently filtered or deleted when undefined. For distances exceeding the rod length, θ is set to NaN, preserving the dipole while preventing unphysical values.

Zero-Distance Dipole Handling
For dipoles where the measured distance is exactly 0 nm, the azimuth direction is physically undefined. In these cases, no orientation arrow is drawn in scatter plots, and a visible “NaN” label is shown instead. The dipole remains in the dataset and all statistics.

Dipole Tracking Across Frames
Dipoles are tracked across time by computing midpoints between paired puncta and linking midpoints across frames using a distance-based assignment. 
Each dipole trajectory is assigned a consistent Track ID, enabling time-resolved analysis.

Outputs

The pipeline generates multiple diagnostic and analysis plots, including:
01) End-to-end distance histograms
02) Azimuth angle versus distance scatter plots
03) Theta-colored midpoint maps
04) Phi-colored midpoint maps
05) Orientation arrow plots with safeguards for undefined angles

Tracked dipole data are saved to an Excel file named Tracked_Dipoles.xlsx, containing a master sheet and individual sheets for each tracked dipole.

